{"title":"SRAM Goes Full Gravel with RED XPLR 13 Speed Groupset","link":"https://bikerumor.com/sram-red-xplr-13-speed-groupset/","date":1722520800000,"content":"<p><img src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Groupset--1536x1099.png\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1099\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Groupset\" /></p>\n<p>After SRAM chummed the water with some <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/new-sram-transmission-gravel-group-spotted-at-unbound-13-speed-axs-xplr/\">not-so-secret spy shots </a>of the unreleased 13-speed SRAM RED XPLR groupset, most of the gravel world sat waiting, cash in hand. Well, it’s finally out, with details and some <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-admin/post.php?post=365335&amp;action=edit\">bonus products that will make your head spin</a> — so let’s get to it!  </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-close-up--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a><figcaption>(All Photos: Jordan Villella/Bikerumor)</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>What is SRAM RED XPLR? </h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The latest release follows the new <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/new-sram-red-axs-unveiled-tech-details-those-brakes/\">SRAM RED groupset</a>. The updated group improves many small details but dramatically improves braking and lever feel. SRAM decided to make this jump while everything fell into place. The SRAM Transmission mountain bike group used the UDH to create a bombproof rear derailleur, and the existing XLPR line drifted into gravel territory. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>A proper mixture of mountain and road from the SRAM groupset universe formed.  So why not? </em></p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-casette-installed--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>Why 13 Speeds? </h3>\n\n\n\n<p>The first question that comes to mind with “new or more gears” is, “<em>is this a new standard?”</em> However, the new RED XPLR group set uses the same XDR driver body as the 12-speed group sets and the same chain, so there is no new standard. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-13-speed--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>How? </strong>The unique cassette angles over the spokes and doesn’t take up any more space on the cassette body. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>New Chain?</strong> Sort of—but no. This is the same flattop 12-speed chain you’ll find on the new SRAM RED but with some extra bling.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--scaled.\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-installed--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>SRAM RED XPLR Derailleur </h3>\n\n\n\n<p>If you’re familiar with the <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/sram-transmission-eagle-mountain-bike-drivetrain/\">SRAM Transmission mountain bike groupset</a>, the new RED XPLR derailleur won’t surprise you. However, there are some very cool gravel—and drop bar-specific additions. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>What’s the “same”?</em></strong> There is a lot of carry over from the Transmission world including the same AXS batteries, the same Magic wheel (genius), zero limit screws, and of course, a UDH mount. Maintenance, installation, and troubleshooting are precisely the same as the transmission line, and the same goes for chain sizing using the SRAM chain length calculator. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>How about interchangeable parts with Transmission? </em></strong>The pulley set from the Transmission derailleurs and the GX Transmission rear derailleur battery latch are interchangeable with the RED XPLR AXS rear derailleur. SRAM states that these are the only parts of the derailleurs that can be used interchangeably. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-Magic-wheel-2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The XPLR line is specific to the length of the cage and some bits to lighten up the derailleur to be worthy of the SRAM RED naming convention. The entire derailleur is rebuildable, and parts are all replaceable except for the front, where “RED” is engraved. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The new design will only work with the SRAM 10-46T XPLR 13-speed cassette and road Flattop chains. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-dome--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>SRAM XPLR Cassette</h3>\n\n\n\n<p>The cassette is the most excellent stand-alone piece of the SRAM RED XPLR groupset. It reminds me of the first power-dome RED cassettes, which were a work of art and loud, haha. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The XPLR cassette, however, draws on years of product knowledge and delivers a good look and functional design. The cassette mimics the Transmission design with a block of road/gravel gears. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-assemply--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It offers a 460% range, and if paired with the right front ring, you should be able to climb anything. Like the transmission groupset, the cassette shifts the best under load and force. Something that is usually a no-no, given the torque produced in the lower gears. This (like Transmission) makes the groupset a real option for e-bike and e-gravel riders, shifting under load constantly. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The gearing jumps are tight for the four highest gears, then skip a tooth for the next three, and get further spaced out as you travel up the cassette. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>SRAM XPLR cassette tooth count</strong>: 10,11,12,13,15,17,19,21,24,28,32,38 and finally 46T</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-crankset--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>SRAM XPLR Crankset and Powermeter </h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Unlike Shimano, SRAM went all-in with power and redesigned chainrings for their RED XPLR crankset. Like the transmission mountain bike crankset, the crankset uses a thread-on chainring available in many gravel-specific sizes (38T-46T). </p>\n\n\n\n<p>For those looking to harness the power, the new SRAM RED XPLR crankset with power boasts dual side power capture, 200 hours of battery life with a replaceable coin cell battery, and IPX7 waterproof protection. Perfect for those creek crossings; don’t stay under water longer than 30 minutes. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1919\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-details--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The crankset itself is a SRAM RED design (the same as the latest release), available with or without a power meter. Those not power-hungry can opt for the direct-mount single chainrings, available in the exact 38T-46T sizing. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--scaled\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-lever-shape--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>SRAM RED XPLR Shifters / Brakes </h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Some items, including the shifters and brakes, are carried over from the SRAM RED launch. Yes, the shifters now go up to 13 points on the cassette, but the brake lever and caliper are the same. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>It seems like more cross-over. What’s backward compatible?</em></strong><em> </em>The SRAM RED XPLR AXS will work with prior generations. It is also compatible with all AXS controls, all road Flattop chains, and all wide 1x crank arms. However, because the 13-speed Full Mount rear derailleur is optimized to work with the RED XPLR XG-1391 cassette, those drivetrain parts are not backward compatible. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-button-2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>I wanted to touch on the shifter and brake setup quickly. The design is more than refined; it is a complete overhaul. The lever pull has an ease I’ve never felt in SRAM road brakes. The caliper body looks more like a CNC machined one-off than a forged or cast production piece.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--scaled.\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-brake--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>I didn’t cover the RED road launch, so this was new to me when I experienced it with the RED XLPR gear – this was a serious brake performance update. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-group--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>SRAM RED XPLR Pricing</h2>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>XPLR Rear Derailleur</strong>:USD: $700.00, EUR: €630.00, GBP: £540.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Red E1 Flattop Chain</strong>: USD: $99.00, EUR: €89.00, GBP: £76.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Red XPLR Cassette</strong>: USD: $600.00, EUR: €585.00, GBP: £500.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Red XPLR Crankset (non-power)</strong>: USD: $650.00 (chainring included), EUR: €585.00, GBP: £500.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Red XPLR Crankset Power </strong>(chainring included):, USD: $1,100.00, EUR: €990.00, GBP: £850.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Separate Chainrings</strong>:USD: $150.00, EUR: €135.00, GBP: £115.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Paceline X Rotor</strong>: USD: $70.00, EUR: €63.00, GBP: £54.00</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>SRAM RED Shifter/Brake lever</strong>: USD: $675.00, EUR: €608.00, GBP: £520.00</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<h2>SRAM RED XPLR Weights </h2>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-derail-with-battery-weight--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rear-derail-with-battery-weight--1536x1152.jpeg\" 