eg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Dub-BB-t47-weight--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Dub-BB-t47-weight--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Dub-BB-t47-weight--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Dub-BB-t47-weight--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--1536x1152.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-chain-weight--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--1536x1152.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-rotor-weight--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--1536x1152.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-shifterss-weight--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--1536x1152.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-cassette-weight--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>SRAM XPLR Derailleur: 375g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>SRAM XPLR cassette: 289g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>SRAM XPLR Rotor: 132g (no lock ring)</li>\n\n\n\n<li>SRAM Dub BB T47: 87g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>SRAM RED Chain: 250g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>SRAM XPLR Crankset 40T Power: 514g</li>\n\n\n\n<li>SRAM RED Brake/Shift Lever (with hose and caliper): 370g</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-full-bike--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>First Impressions: SRAM RED XPLR Review</h3>\n\n\n\n<p>I was pumped when SRAM let the cat out of the bag. They were making a gravel-specific groupset. I knew the new groupset had better braking performance, and they are dedicated to the 1x drive train; it could be fantastic. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Spyshots revealed a lovely mix of the Transmission mountain bike design and the new iteration of RED… but with an extra gear. After learning the new groupset required no new standard or chain, I was extra curious. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>Install and Build </h3>\n\n\n\n<p>When the groupset arrived, I followed the SRAM instructions to the “T” and was pleasantly surprised to have an uneventful time with the assembly. Most review bikes come fully assembled, and we dial them in, but rarely do I build a frame from the bottom up, especially with new gear. But the instructions were spot on, the brakes were very easy to set up/bleed, and the chain sizing was foolproof. I used the new Park Tool 13 spd chain tool, and though the chain is still a “12-speed” design, it worked excellently. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--1536x1152.jpeg\" alt=\"13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--scaled\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/13-speed-chain-tool-park-tool-close-up--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"1536\" height=\"1152\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--1536x1152.jpeg\" alt=\"Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Park-tool-13-speed-chain-tool--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The RED XPLR uses the same setup as Transmission MTB; the setup cog is highlighted with an orange band (the grey ones are to deaden the sound of the cassette). You size the chain with the rear derailleur in setup mode (a click between fully open and engaged to ride). Pull the body tight so the chain is engaged, and tighten the UDH fixing bolt to torque, allowing the two lines on the hanger to meet up. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-side-lever--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Ride Ready </h2>\n\n\n\n<p>After the installation, I was eager to get on the road, so I slapped on some wheels (the Zipp 303 XPLR wheels were still in the mail). The first thing I noticed was the braking performance. I’ve ridden the previous RED groupset for a while. Every iteration gets slightly better from the first RED hydro brake, but not “wow” better. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rider-view--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>This version <em>is</em> WOW better and perfectly fits the style of gravel riding.  One-finger braking is easy, and the lever feels smooth and fluid. The lever body melts in your hand and allows for a full hand on the lever. Plus – there is a bonus button, one that’s easily programable and tactile.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--scaled.\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-rotor--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Shifting Speed </h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The shifting is quicker than the Transmission MTB (or it feels that way) and very smooth. The cassette jumps, and a 40T front ring seem spot-on for my riding style. The higher end of the cluster is tightly spaced and allows for a cadence dial-in and metered effort. As you travel up the cassette, the jumps are more significant until you reach the “save me” 46T cog. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Like the Transmission MTB groupsets, the RED XPLR group shifts exceptionally well under load. You can shift quickly when chugging along on chunky gravel, spinning a slow cadence. The same goes for climbing and shifting to a higher gear for an all-out attack. It lacks that “ca-chunk” shifting sound and feels more like a slightly increased pressure on the pedals. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-UDH-2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>Chain Retention </h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Chain retention is well managed, and I didn’t drop a chain during my test periods—believe me, I tried. The slightly smaller cage of the RED XPLR derailleur holds the chain nicely without affecting the feel while pedaling. I attribute this to the chain sizing tool as well. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal-\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-crankset-ring-removal--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The crankset is a nice mix of road and MTB. The spin-on chainring is very dialed and something I liked from the Transmission XX SL cranksets. It does require a specific tool to remove the ring (above), and it is available separately if you’re like me and like to swap rings constantly like a track racer.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--scaled.jpeg\"><img width=\"2560\" height=\"1920\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--scaled.jpeg\" alt=\"SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--scaled.jpeg 2560w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--297x223.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--120x90.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--768x576.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SRAM-RED-XPLR-Installed-levers--2048x1536.jpeg 2048w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3>So Far, So Good</h3>\n\n\n\n<p>I’m reserving my full thoughts for a longer (months) review period, but I’m very impressed so far. Yes, it’s a RED groupset, so it’s pricy, but the performance is fantastic, and the progress should (hopefully) hit the FORCE and APEX groups. However, the cassette will be tough to get down in price from $600 to something more palatable to the public. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>As of right now, I’m very happy with the SRAM RED XPLR groupset. The performance in shifting, braking, and overall ease of use is top-notch. Look for a full review as we put the RED XPLR group through the paces and even some cyclocross racing early in the fall. </p>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.sram.com\">SRAM.com</a></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/sram-red-xplr-13-speed-groupset/\">SRAM Goes Full Gravel with RED XPLR 13 Speed Groupset </a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com\">Bikerumor</a>.</p>","author":"Jordan Villella","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"22e2aa64fc86be3b0e7a9cd3ee9fbd25f5c83f07e8ed731b0f74288d81331774","category":"Cycling"}